const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How much vitamin C should I take daily?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The Recommended Dietary Allowance (RDA) for vitamin C is 90mg per day for adult men and 75mg for adult women, with smokers needing an additional 35mg. However, the RDA represents the minimum to prevent deficiency (scurvy), not necessarily the optimal intake for immune function. Research on immune support suggests that 200-500mg per day maximizes plasma vitamin C levels and immune cell saturation. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level (UL) is 2,000mg per day — doses above this may cause gastrointestinal distress including diarrhea. Most vitamin C gummies provide 125-250mg per serving, which is well within the optimal immune support range.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do vitamin C gummies really boost immunity?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Vitamin C plays a critical role in immune function by supporting both the innate and adaptive immune systems. It accumulates in neutrophils and lymphocytes at concentrations 10-100 times higher than plasma levels, enabling these immune cells to kill pathogens through oxidative burst. A 2017 review in the journal Nutrients concluded that vitamin C supplementation at 200mg or more per day reduced the duration of common cold symptoms by 8% in adults and 14% in children. It does not prevent colds in the general population but does reduce severity and duration. For individuals under physical stress (athletes, soldiers), vitamin C at 200-1000mg per day reduced cold incidence by approximately 50%.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the best form of vitamin C in gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Ascorbic acid is the most common and well-studied form of vitamin C, with the highest bioavailability data. Sodium ascorbate is a buffered form that is gentler on the stomach, making it preferable for individuals with acid sensitivity. Calcium ascorbate provides vitamin C plus a small amount of calcium. Ascorbyl palmitate is a fat-soluble form with potentially longer tissue retention. For most people, plain ascorbic acid is optimal. The differences in bioavailability between forms are small — a 2013 study in Nutrients found no significant difference in plasma vitamin C levels between ascorbic acid and buffered forms at equivalent doses.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I take too much vitamin C?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Vitamin C is water-soluble, meaning excess amounts are excreted in urine rather than stored in fat tissue. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level is 2,000mg per day for adults. Doses above this threshold increase the risk of gastrointestinal side effects including nausea, diarrhea, and abdominal cramps. Very high doses (above 3,000mg per day) have been associated with increased oxalate excretion, which may elevate kidney stone risk in susceptible individuals. Most vitamin C gummies provide 125-250mg per serving, making it difficult to reach the UL through gummies alone unless you dramatically exceed the recommended serving size.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Are vitamin C gummies as effective as tablets?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, vitamin C gummies are comparably effective to tablets when they contain the same dose of ascorbic acid. The vitamin C molecule is identical regardless of delivery format. A 2015 study published in the Journal of the American Nutrition Association compared plasma vitamin C levels after gummy and tablet supplementation at equivalent doses and found no statistically significant difference in absorption or bioavailability. The primary advantage of gummies is adherence — the pleasant taste and chewable format improves daily compliance, and consistent intake is the most important factor for maintaining optimal vitamin C status.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Should I take vitamin C with zinc for immune support?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Combining vitamin C with zinc provides complementary immune benefits. Vitamin C supports immune cell function and acts as an antioxidant, while zinc is essential for immune cell development and communication, particularly T-cell and natural killer cell activity. A 2012 Cochrane review found that zinc lozenges (75mg per day) reduced cold duration by 33% when started within 24 hours of symptom onset. The combination of vitamin C and zinc addresses two distinct immune pathways simultaneously. Several products in this guide include zinc alongside vitamin C for comprehensive immune defense.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When is the best time to take vitamin C gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Vitamin C can be taken at any time of day, as it does not cause drowsiness or stimulation. However, absorption may be slightly enhanced when taken with food, particularly meals containing iron, as vitamin C significantly increases non-heme iron absorption. Taking vitamin C with breakfast is the most common recommendation because it establishes a daily routine that promotes consistency. If you experience stomach sensitivity with vitamin C on an empty stomach, taking it with a meal eliminates this issue. Split dosing (half morning, half evening) can maintain higher sustained plasma levels throughout the day.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Does cooking destroy vitamin C in food?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, vitamin C is the most heat-sensitive of all vitamins. Boiling vegetables can destroy 50-80% of their vitamin C content, while steaming retains approximately 70-90%. Microwaving with minimal water preserves the most vitamin C due to shorter cooking times. Raw fruits and vegetables deliver the highest vitamin C content. This heat sensitivity is one reason supplementation can be valuable — it provides a consistent, known dose regardless of diet composition and cooking methods. Individuals who eat primarily cooked foods may benefit most from vitamin C supplementation to close the gap between dietary intake and optimal immune levels.' },
    },
  ],
};
