    <h2 id="why-vitamin-c">Why Vitamin C Remains the Foundation of Immune Defense</h2>

    <p>Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) is the single most important water-soluble antioxidant in the human body and a critical cofactor for immune cell function. Unlike most mammals, humans lost the ability to synthesize vitamin C endogenously approximately 61 million years ago due to a mutation in the L-gulonolactone oxidase (GULO) gene. This means every milligram of vitamin C in your body must come from dietary sources or supplementation — there is no internal backup system.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">200mg</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">per day is the dose at which plasma vitamin C levels and immune cell saturation reach a plateau, according to pharmacokinetic research published in the <strong>Annals of Internal Medicine</strong>. Doses above 200mg produce progressively smaller increases in blood levels due to renal excretion. This is the optimal daily target for immune support — well above the RDA of 75-90mg but below the 2,000mg Upper Limit.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Within the immune system, vitamin C accumulates in neutrophils at concentrations 10-100 times higher than plasma levels, powering the oxidative burst that kills ingested pathogens. It also supports T-cell proliferation, enhances antibody production, and protects immune cells from the oxidative damage generated during inflammatory responses. Vitamin C deficiency impairs immune function before any clinical signs of scurvy appear — subclinical deficiency may be far more common than recognized, particularly in smokers, the elderly, and individuals with limited fruit and vegetable intake.</p>

