    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Vitamin C Forms Explained: Bioavailability, Tolerance, and Optimal Dosing</h4>
      <p>The form of vitamin C in your gummy affects absorption speed, stomach tolerance, and tissue retention. Here is what the research says about each form commonly found in gummy supplements.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Ascorbic Acid (L-Ascorbic Acid)</strong>
          <p>The most studied form with the most bioavailability data. Identical to the vitamin C naturally found in fruits. Rapidly absorbed with peak plasma levels in 1-2 hours. May cause mild GI discomfort in sensitive individuals at high doses. Used in most gummies in this guide.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Sodium Ascorbate (Buffered C)</strong>
          <p>Ascorbic acid buffered with sodium to raise pH. Gentler on the stomach — preferred for individuals with acid reflux or gastritis. Provides approximately 11% sodium by weight. Same bioavailability as ascorbic acid in comparative studies.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Whole-Food Vitamin C (Amla, Acerola)</strong>
          <p>Vitamin C derived from fruit extracts. Naturally contains bioflavonoids that may enhance retention. Lower doses per serving due to extraction limitations. Slight bioavailability advantage in some studies, though clinical significance is debated.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Optimal Dosing Strategy</strong>
          <p>200-250mg per day saturates immune cells without excessive renal excretion. Split dosing (morning + evening) maintains higher 24-hour plasma levels than a single dose. Pair with bioflavonoid-rich foods (citrus pith, berries) for enhanced retention.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Iron absorption boost:</strong> Vitamin C dramatically enhances non-heme iron absorption — by 2-3x when taken simultaneously. If you take an iron supplement, pairing it with your vitamin C gummy can significantly improve iron bioavailability. This is particularly relevant for women of reproductive age and vegetarians, who are at higher risk of iron deficiency.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
        <p><strong>Mega-dosing is wasteful, not harmful:</strong> Your kidneys excrete vitamin C above plasma saturation levels (typically reached at 200-400mg intake). Taking 1000mg of vitamin C does not provide 4x the benefit of 250mg — it provides the same immune cell saturation plus expensive urine. Unless specifically directed by a physician for a medical condition, doses above 500mg per day offer diminishing returns for healthy adults.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- HOW WE TESTED -->
    <div class="tested-box">
      <h3>How We Tested These Vitamin C Gummies</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Purchased independently.</strong> Every product was purchased at full retail price from Amazon or the brand's direct website. No product was provided free of charge, and no brand was informed of this evaluation in advance.</li>
        <li><strong>Verified vitamin C content and form.</strong> We analyzed the supplement facts panel of each product to confirm the vitamin C form (ascorbic acid, sodium ascorbate, whole-food extract), dose per serving, and whether the dose falls within the clinically optimal range of 200-500mg.</li>
        <li><strong>Prioritized third-party verification.</strong> Products with USP Verification, NSF certification, or publicly available certificates of analysis received higher quality scores. We contacted each manufacturer directly to request third-party testing documentation.</li>
        <li><strong>Evaluated immune support additions.</strong> We scored bonus ingredients (zinc, vitamin D, elderberry, echinacea, bioflavonoids) based on their independent clinical evidence for immune support and the doses provided relative to clinically studied amounts.</li>
        <li><strong>Assessed taste and compliance factors.</strong> Eight editorial team members rated each product on taste, texture, aftertaste, and overall daily compliance willingness on a 1-10 scale. Flavor quality directly impacts whether consumers take their gummies consistently.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculated long-term value.</strong> Cost per serving, cost per milligram of vitamin C, and cost per month were computed to enable accurate cross-product comparison independent of bottle size and marketing positioning.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

