    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin C Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much vitamin C should I take daily?</summary>
      <p>The RDA is 90mg for men and 75mg for women, but research on immune support suggests 200-500mg per day maximizes plasma levels and immune cell saturation. The Tolerable Upper Intake Level is 2,000mg per day. Most vitamin C gummies provide 125-250mg per serving, well within the optimal range. Smokers need an additional 35mg above the standard RDA due to increased oxidative stress.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do vitamin C gummies really boost immunity?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin C plays a critical role in immune function by supporting both innate and adaptive immunity. It accumulates in neutrophils at concentrations 10-100 times higher than plasma levels. A 2017 review in <em>Nutrients</em> found that vitamin C at 200mg+ per day reduced cold duration by 8% in adults and 14% in children. It does not prevent colds in the general population but reduces severity and duration. In physically stressed individuals, vitamin C reduced cold incidence by approximately 50%.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the best form of vitamin C in gummies?</summary>
      <p>Ascorbic acid is the most common and well-studied form with the highest bioavailability data. Sodium ascorbate is a buffered form that is gentler on the stomach. Whole-food sources (amla berry, acerola cherry) naturally contain bioflavonoids that may enhance retention. A 2013 study in <em>Nutrients</em> found no significant difference in plasma levels between ascorbic acid and buffered forms at equivalent doses. For most people, plain ascorbic acid is optimal.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take too much vitamin C?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin C is water-soluble and excess is excreted in urine. The Upper Limit is 2,000mg per day. Doses above this may cause nausea, diarrhea, and abdominal cramps. Very high doses (3,000mg+) may increase kidney stone risk in susceptible individuals. Most gummies provide 125-250mg per serving, making it difficult to reach the UL through gummies alone.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Are vitamin C gummies as effective as tablets?</summary>
      <p>Yes, vitamin C gummies are comparably effective to tablets at the same dose. The molecule is identical regardless of delivery format. A 2015 study found no statistically significant difference in absorption between gummy and tablet formats at equivalent doses. The primary advantage of gummies is adherence — the pleasant taste improves daily compliance, and consistent intake is the most important factor for maintaining optimal vitamin C status.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Should I take vitamin C with zinc for immune support?</summary>
      <p>Combining vitamin C with zinc provides complementary immune benefits through different pathways. Vitamin C supports immune cell function and acts as an antioxidant, while zinc is essential for T-cell and natural killer cell development. A 2012 Cochrane review found zinc reduced cold duration by 33% when started within 24 hours of symptoms. Products like Emergen-C and SmartyPants include both nutrients for comprehensive immune defense.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When is the best time to take vitamin C gummies?</summary>
      <p>Vitamin C can be taken at any time of day. Absorption may be slightly enhanced with food, particularly meals containing iron (vitamin C increases non-heme iron absorption by 2-3x). Taking it with breakfast establishes a daily routine. Split dosing (half morning, half evening) can maintain higher sustained plasma levels throughout the day.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does cooking destroy vitamin C in food?</summary>
      <p>Yes, vitamin C is the most heat-sensitive vitamin. Boiling destroys 50-80% of vitamin C content, while steaming retains 70-90%. Raw fruits and vegetables deliver the highest content. This is one reason supplementation can be valuable — it provides a consistent, known dose regardless of cooking methods. Individuals who eat primarily cooked foods benefit most from supplementation.</p>
    </details>

